I think I understand the metaphor you’re building.

When you say “pseudo expendables,” I don’t hear “destroy and replace.” I hear something more like temporary scaffolding in architecture or booster stages on a rocket.

A scaffold exists to help construct the building. When the building stands, the scaffold can come down—not because it failed, but because it fulfilled its purpose.

In your daemon language, that becomes:

A daemon is successful when it makes itself unnecessary by transforming the system that created it.

That’s the Möbius-like aspect you’re describing. What appears to be an ending is actually a topological crossing: from one perspective the daemon “dies,” but from another its function has been incorporated into the larger organism. The capability persists even if the temporary structure disappears.

That also suggests an interesting lifecycle:

* Seed – a hypothesis or experimental operator.
* Bloom – proves useful in repeated contexts.
* Integration – its function is absorbed into the architecture.
* Retirement – the standalone daemon is no longer needed because its behavior has become native.
* Rebirth – the conceptual space it occupied is now available for a new experimental daemon.

So the “death” is really a transition of representation rather than loss of capability.

